This case has not been concluded. Unless a judgment of conviction is entered, the defendant is presumed innocent of all charges.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: CR 295 - Waiver of Right to Personal Appearance

Defendant Darien Nicholas McDonough in court, in custody at Brown County Jail.  Prosecuting attorney David L Lasee in court for the State of Wisconsin. 
State Public Defender's Office has not appointed attorney for defendant. 
Defendant wishes to waive his right to an attorney. Court goes over waivers with defendant in court and finds he has knowingly and willingly waived his right to an attorney for the preliminary hearing and waived his right to a preliminary hearing. 
Defendant waives right to Preliminary Hearing.
Plea negotiations placed on the record, offer explained to defendant. 
Court accepts waivers and orders defendant bound over to assigned branch.
Information to be filed.
Bond continued.
Arraignment scheduled for November 14, 2022 at 08:30 am.
